<br />
Then we have, "We are now simply trying to make the rest of the world act in our best interests by force..."  This is just not correct.  First off, we haven&#39;t threatened the rest of the world.  Quite the opposite -- we&#39;ve gone well out of our way to include them.  We&#39;ve focused any threats on Iraq, because the country is run by a known murderer and rapist, who keeps company with a government of murderers and rapists to make himself feel better.  These schmucks have VX and mustard gas and who knows what all else, and have never demonstrated the slightest hesitation in using any of it.  To ask them to comply with the regulations that they agreed to as a part of the cease-fire in &#39;91 is not unreasonable.  C&#39;mon, if Germany had refused to give up it&#39;s remaining tanks and bombs and planes after World War II, do you think Britain and Russia and the U.S. would have stood around and debated what to do?  Of course not.  Same type of situation, just with weapons that are a whole lot nastier.<br />
<br />
Secondly, it is not only OUR best interests we&#39;re working towards here.  Quite frankly, I don&#39;t see how it&#39;s in ANYONE&#39;s best interests if Iraq maintains the ability to kill ten thousand plus people whenever Saddam feels like it (except, perhaps, his own best interests, because it keeps him in the center of attention).  You haven&#39;t heard Iran complaining about disarming Saddam, have you?  Probably because they know first-hand that he&#39;ll use everything in his arsenal if he feels like he can get away with it.  <br />
<br />
