It is very hard not to look at it in a historical context. Nuclear Weapons used to be a deterent against major powers bent on world domination (Germany, Japan, the USSR, China). We had pretty clear evidence that these countries, at various times, intended global domination by conquest and or revolution. These threats were credible and substantiated by behavior (Nazi Germany attempts to conquer Europe, Japan does the same in Asia and bombs Pearl Harbor, the USSR drops the Iron Curtain over Eastern Europe, China sponsors North Korea and North Vietnam). All of these regimes espoused doctrines that pretty clearly stated their plans for world domination ("We will bury you!" -- Nikita Kruschev). We felt vulnerable to conquest and that our way of life was threatened. We used to have air raid drills in school because the USSR had planes and missiles that could reach our country and blow us all to oblivion. That was the perceived threat that we were countering. <br />
<br />
This statement represents a serious change in the USA&#39;s attitude. We are no longer dealing with perceived threats to our own existance. We are now simply trying to make the rest of the world act in our best interests by force and making it clear that, if our enemies take desparate measures, we will obliterate them rather than simply conquering them. <br />
